stocks.news:
Nvidia Earnings Beat:

Investors were calling Nvidia's (NVDA +1.44%) earnings report last night a "make or break" moment.

What happened? The company beat Wall St. expectations for Q4 2025 earnings, as well as future outlook. The company expects $5B more in revenue in Q1 than analysts predicted ‚Äî and that's assuming no revenue from China.

The stock's performance has been mostly flat for several months, but rose 3% in after-hours trading.

economy.commentary:
The New 401k Plan:

President Trump unveiled a new 401k/retirement plan during Tuesday's State of the Union address.

How it works: Trump says the government will match $1k annually for people to save in a retirement account.

Who's eligible? Workers who do not already have access to an employer-sponsored 401k ‚Äî around 56M people.

Lower Rates, More Refinances:

Mortgage rates have now hit their lowest rate in years, spurring a wave of refinances.

An index that tracks refinancing activity spiked up more than 4%, and refinancing activity has trended higher throughout the year as rates fall.

But: There hasn't been a strong wave of buying activity, despite the lower rates.

crypto.commentary:
Coinbase Adds Stock Trading:

Coinbase (COIN +13.52%) shares took off yesterday, trading up more than 10% on news that it officially added stock trading to its platform.

That means that users will be able to trade shares of stocks 24/7, in addition to cryptos on the app.

Coinbase has said it wants to become the "everything exchange," allowing users to trade basically anything.

real_estate.homebuilder: Homebuilders remain cautious as industry leaders predict remodeling will outshine new construction in 2026 due to high material costs and mortgage rates expected to stay above 6% through the year.
real_estate.commentary:
The Bay Area is seeing a "tale of two markets" with single-family homes selling quickly in under 20 days while the condo market has slowed significantly, with units sitting for an average of 51 to 55 days.

Latest Real Estate News in the Bay Area:

üè° Diverging Values in the East Bay: Single-family home prices in Alameda County have seen a turnaround, rising 2.86% year-over-year to a median of $1,150,000. Conversely, the condominium market remains under pressure with a 6.36% decline in median prices and nearly double the time on market compared to detached homes.

üè° Silicon Valley Inventory Squeeze: Santa Clara County continues to face an acute supply shortage, with single-family inventory down 12% compared to last year. The market remains firmly in seller territory with less than one month of supply (0.9 MSI), though median prices saw a modest annual dip of 3.89% to approximately $1.73 million.

üè° Shifting Buyer Leverage: While single-family homes in prime areas like Fremont and Milpitas still move rapidly, buyers are gaining more negotiating power in the condo segment. Seasonal cooling has brought more balance to attached housing, where days on market and market absorption have increased significantly.

Latest General News in the Bay Area:

üì∞ Community Mourning in Milpitas: The local community is mourning a 29-year-old Milpitas motorcyclist who tragically succumbed to his injuries following a solo collision with a traffic island in Newark earlier this month.

üì∞ Fremont Civic Updates: The Fremont Fire Department and Newark Police recently handled major traffic fatalities while local school boards and community centers prepare for upcoming March job fairs and student internship events.

üì∞ Milpitas Dining Milestone: Local residents are bidding a final farewell to Koong's, a staple Chinese restaurant in Milpitas that officially closed its doors after more than 40 years of service to the community.
